  "opinion": "As a creative, upper secondary student in Los Angeles who’s navigating STEM fields with a background of one parent with a master’s and one without formal education, I’ve seen firsthand how stereotype threat can silently undermine potential. Stereotype threat isn’t just a buzzword—it’s the quiet anxiety that hits when you’re reminded you’re part of a group historically marginalized in science. For me, it’s the moment I’d glance at a math problem, heart pounding, wondering if I’m ‘not good enough’ because I’m a girl in a field dominated by men. It’s the hesitation to speak up in class, fearing my voice will be dismissed as ‘too emotional’ or ‘not technical enough.’ This isn’t about individual failure—it’s about systemic whispers that tell us we don’t belong. And yes, we absolutely must address it. In my community, we’ve started small: mentorship programs that pair girls with female engineers, workshops that normalize asking questions without shame, and classrooms where success stories are shared openly. These efforts aren’t just good for morale—they’re practical. When students feel seen and supported, their performance improves. I’ve seen it firsthand in my own experience: after joining a local coding club focused on inclusivity, I stopped second-guessing my abilities and started solving problems with confidence. The key isn’t just changing policies but creating a culture where everyone feels safe to explore their potential. As someone who values both creativity and practical problem-solving, I believe this work is essential to building a future where STEM isn’t a place of exclusion but of endless possibility.",
